{"cursor":"10112","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nThe 'amplitude' of a periodic variable is a measure of its change over a single\nperiod (such as time or spatial period). There are various definitions of\namplitude (see below), which are all functions of the magnitude of the\ndifference between the variable's extreme values.\n\nIn older texts the phase is sometimes called the amplitude.\n","linknr":270,"url":"Amplitude","recorded":1362485892,"links":69,"instances":["physics","physics","mathematics","signal_processing","vector","electricity","waves","physics","signal_processing"],"pdf":["http://orca.phys.uvic.ca/~tatum/celmechs/celm18.pdf","http://img2.tapuz.co.il/forums/1_109580628.pdf"],"categories":["Physical quantities","Sound","Concepts in physics","Wave mechanics"],"headings":["Definitions of the term","Formal representation","Waveform and envelope","See also","Notes"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Sine_voltage.svg/220px-Sine_voltage.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/9/c/69c5487b20876c2d2c939674d9b79ad3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/9/5/495ad43ec221b4548c338a2797c4d150.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/a/0da281bb9014bef25d92b71674201427.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/0/d/70de78722a34de193b00798550662b45.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/c/6/1c6104794d77d5dea70b9ead506f325b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/62/PD-icon.svg/12px-PD-icon.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["variable",